1
00:00:01,904 --> 00:00:06,778
So let's take a look at how we can
develop a recommended system if we had

2
00:00:06,778 --> 00:00:10,343
features of each item, or
features of each movie.

3
00:00:10,343 --> 00:00:15,259
So here's the same data set that we
had previously with the four users

4
00:00:15,259 --> 00:00:18,750
having rated some but
not all of the five movies.

5
00:00:18,750 --> 00:00:22,550
What if we additionally have
features of the movies?

6
00:00:22,550 --> 00:00:27,668
So here I've added two features X1 and
X2, that tell us how much

7
00:00:27,668 --> 00:00:33,829
each of these is a romance movie, and
how much each of these is an action movie.

8
00:00:33,829 --> 00:00:37,472
So for example Love at Last
is a very romantic movie, so

9
00:00:37,472 --> 00:00:42,004
this feature takes on 0.9, but
it's not at all an action movie.

10
00:00:42,004 --> 00:00:45,245
So this feature takes on 0.

11
00:00:45,245 --> 00:00:50,034
But it turns out Nonstop Car chases has
just a little bit of romance in it.

12
00:00:50,034 --> 00:00:54,023
So it's 0.1, but it has a ton of action.

13
00:00:54,023 --> 00:00:57,619
So that feature takes on the value of 1.0.

14
00:00:57,619 --> 00:01:04,050
So you recall that I had used the notation
nu to denote the number of users,

15
00:01:04,050 --> 00:01:09,157
which is 4 and m to denote
the number of movies which is 5.

16
00:01:09,157 --> 00:01:14,003
I'm going to also introduce n to denote
the number of features we have here.

17
00:01:14,003 --> 00:01:19,897
And so n=2, because we have two
features X1 and X2 for each movie.

18
00:01:19,897 --> 00:01:25,520
With these features we have for
example that the features for

19
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:31,372
movie one, that is the movie Love at Last,
would be 0.90.

20
00:01:31,372 --> 00:01:35,406
And the features for the third movie

21
00:01:35,406 --> 00:01:40,661
Cute Puppies of Love would be 0.99 and 0.

22
00:01:40,661 --> 00:01:46,248
And let's start by taking a look at
how we might make predictions for

23
00:01:46,248 --> 00:01:48,415
Alice's movie ratings.

24
00:01:48,415 --> 00:01:52,767
So for user one, that is Alice,

25
00:01:52,767 --> 00:01:57,606
let's say we predict the rating for

26
00:01:57,606 --> 00:02:01,163
movie i as w.X(i)+b.

27
00:02:01,163 --> 00:02:05,395
So this is just a lot
like linear regression.

28
00:02:05,395 --> 00:02:12,072
For example if we end up choosing
the parameter w(1)=[5,0] and

29
00:02:12,072 --> 00:02:16,012
say b(1)=0, then the prediction for

30
00:02:16,012 --> 00:02:22,827
movie three where
the features are 0.99 and 0,

31
00:02:22,827 --> 00:02:28,067
which is just copied from here,
first feature 0.99, second feature 0.

32
00:02:28,067 --> 00:02:35,003
Our prediction would be w.X(3)+b=0.99

33
00:02:35,003 --> 00:02:38,871
times 5 plus 0 times zero,

34
00:02:38,871 --> 00:02:44,365
which turns out to be equal to 4.95.

35
00:02:44,365 --> 00:02:46,650
And this rating seems pretty plausible.

36
00:02:46,650 --> 00:02:51,951
It looks like Alice has given high ratings
to Love at Last and Romance Forever,

37
00:02:51,951 --> 00:02:57,091
to two highly romantic movies, but
given low ratings to the action movies,

38
00:02:57,091 --> 00:02:59,921
Nonstop Car Chases and Swords vs Karate.

39
00:02:59,921 --> 00:03:02,577
So if we look at Cute Puppies of Love,

40
00:03:02,577 --> 00:03:08,000
well predicting that she might rate
that 4.95 seems quite plausible.

41
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,804
And so these parameters w and b for

42
00:03:10,804 --> 00:03:16,827
Alice seems like a reasonable model for
predicting her movie ratings.

43
00:03:16,827 --> 00:03:21,517
Just add a little the notation
because we have not just one user but

44
00:03:21,517 --> 00:03:24,936
multiple users, or
really nu equals 4 users.

45
00:03:24,936 --> 00:03:31,596
I'm going to add a superscript 1 here to
denote that this is the parameter w(1) for

46
00:03:31,596 --> 00:03:35,124
user 1 and
add a super strip 1 there as well.

47
00:03:35,124 --> 00:03:41,014
And similarly here and here as well,
so that we would actually have

48
00:03:41,014 --> 00:03:46,176
different parameters for
each of the 4 users on data set.

49
00:03:46,176 --> 00:03:51,791
And more generally in this
model we can for user j,

50
00:03:51,791 --> 00:03:58,076
not just user 1 now,
we can predict user j's rating for

51
00:03:58,076 --> 00:04:02,376
movie i as w(j).X(i)+b(j).

52
00:04:02,376 --> 00:04:05,194
So here the parameters w(j) and

53
00:04:05,194 --> 00:04:10,427
b(j) are the parameters used
to predict user j's rating for

54
00:04:10,427 --> 00:04:16,477
movie i which is a function of X(i),
which is the features of movie i.

55
00:04:16,477 --> 00:04:21,271
And this is a lot like linear regression,
except that we're fitting a different

56
00:04:21,271 --> 00:04:25,097
linear regression model for
each of the 4 users in the dataset.

57
00:04:25,097 --> 00:04:30,451
So let's take a look at how we can
formulate the cost function for

58
00:04:30,451 --> 00:04:31,948
this algorithm.

59
00:04:31,948 --> 00:04:37,060
As a reminder on notation
is that r(i.,j)=1

60
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:41,452
if user j has rated movie i or
0 otherwise.

61
00:04:41,452 --> 00:04:46,221
And y(i,j)=rating given
by user j on movie i.

62
00:04:46,221 --> 00:04:51,617
And on the previous side we defined w(j),
b(j) as the parameters for user j.

63
00:04:51,617 --> 00:04:56,717
And X(i) as the feature vector for
movie i.

64
00:04:56,717 --> 00:05:00,429
So the model we have is for user j and

65
00:05:00,429 --> 00:05:06,836
movie i predict the rating
to be w(j).X(i)+b(j).

66
00:05:06,836 --> 00:05:10,624
I'm going to introduce just
one new piece of notation,

67
00:05:10,624 --> 00:05:16,194
which is I'm going to use m(j) to denote
the number of movies rated by user j.

68
00:05:16,194 --> 00:05:21,281
So if the user has rated 4 movies,
then m(j) would be equal to 4.

69
00:05:21,281 --> 00:05:25,990
And if the user has rated 3 movies
then m(j) would be equal to 3.

70
00:05:25,990 --> 00:05:31,716
So what we'd like to do is to
learn the parameters w(j) and

71
00:05:31,716 --> 00:05:35,388
b(j), given the data that we have.

72
00:05:35,388 --> 00:05:40,806
That is given the ratings a user
has given of a set of movies.

73
00:05:40,806 --> 00:05:46,791
So the average we're going to use is
very similar to linear regression.

74
00:05:46,791 --> 00:05:51,258
So let's write out the cost function for
learning the parameters w(j) and

75
00:05:51,258 --> 00:05:52,805
b(j) for a given user j.

76
00:05:52,805 --> 00:05:56,385
And let's just focus on one
user on user j for now.

77
00:05:56,385 --> 00:06:01,411
I'm going to use the mean
squared error criteria.

78
00:06:01,411 --> 00:06:08,263
So the cost will be the prediction,
which is w(j).X(i)+b(j)

79
00:06:08,263 --> 00:06:13,035
minus the actual rating
that the user had given.

80
00:06:13,035 --> 00:06:17,894
So minus y(i,j) squared.

81
00:06:17,894 --> 00:06:21,595
And we're trying to
choose parameters w and

82
00:06:21,595 --> 00:06:26,995
b to minimize the squared error
between the predicted rating and

83
00:06:26,995 --> 00:06:30,207
the actual rating that was observed.

84
00:06:30,207 --> 00:06:35,043
But the user hasn't rated all the movies,
so

85
00:06:35,043 --> 00:06:40,259
if we're going to sum over this,
we're going to

86
00:06:40,259 --> 00:06:46,253
sum over only over the values
of i where r(i,j)=1.

87
00:06:46,253 --> 00:06:53,995
So we're going to sum only over the movies
i that user j has actually rated.

88
00:06:53,995 --> 00:06:59,639
So that's what this denotes,
sum of all values of i where r(i,j)=1.

89
00:06:59,639 --> 00:07:03,610
Meaning that user j has
rated that movie i.

90
00:07:03,610 --> 00:07:11,956
And then finally we can take
the usual normalization 1 over m(j).

91
00:07:11,956 --> 00:07:15,626
And this is very much like
the cost function we have for

92
00:07:15,626 --> 00:07:19,963
linear regression with m or
really m(j) training examples.

93
00:07:19,963 --> 00:07:24,583
Where you're summing over the m(j) movies
for which you have a rating taking

94
00:07:24,583 --> 00:07:28,233
a squared error and
the normalizing by this 1 over 2m(j).

95
00:07:28,233 --> 00:07:32,894
And this is going to be a cost

96
00:07:32,894 --> 00:07:38,375
function J of w(j), b(j).

97
00:07:38,375 --> 00:07:42,765
And if we minimize this as
a function of w(j) and b(j),

98
00:07:42,765 --> 00:07:48,957
then you should come up with a pretty
good choice of parameters w(i) and b(j).

99
00:07:48,957 --> 00:07:51,840
For making predictions for
user j's ratings.

100
00:07:51,840 --> 00:07:54,633
Let me have just one more
term to this cost function,

101
00:07:54,633 --> 00:07:57,811
which is the regularization
term to prevent overfitting.

102
00:07:57,811 --> 00:08:03,314
And so
here's our usual regularization parameter,

103
00:08:03,314 --> 00:08:06,494
lambda divided by 2m(j) and

104
00:08:06,494 --> 00:08:12,619
then times as sum of the squared
values of the parameters w.

105
00:08:12,619 --> 00:08:16,100
And so
n is a number of numbers in X(i) and

106
00:08:16,100 --> 00:08:20,287
that's the same as a number
of numbers in w(j).

107
00:08:20,287 --> 00:08:25,296
If you were to minimize this cost
function J as a function of w and

108
00:08:25,296 --> 00:08:29,452
b, you should get a pretty
good set of parameters for

109
00:08:29,452 --> 00:08:33,350
predicting user j's ratings for
other movies.

110
00:08:33,350 --> 00:08:39,250
Now, before moving on, it turns out
that for recommended systems it would

111
00:08:39,250 --> 00:08:44,591
be convenient to actually eliminate
this division by m(j) term,

112
00:08:44,591 --> 00:08:48,264
m(j) is just a constant
in this expression.

113
00:08:48,264 --> 00:08:50,387
And so, even if you take it out,

114
00:08:50,387 --> 00:08:53,473
you should end up with
the same value of w and b.

115
00:08:53,473 --> 00:08:58,396
Now let me take this cost function
down here to the bottom and

116
00:08:58,396 --> 00:09:00,569
copy it to the next slide.

117
00:09:00,569 --> 00:09:04,753
So we have that to learn
the parameters w(j), b(j) for user j.

118
00:09:04,753 --> 00:09:11,615
We would minimize this cost function
as a function of w(j) and b(j).

119
00:09:11,615 --> 00:09:14,677
But instead of focusing on a single user,

120
00:09:14,677 --> 00:09:19,325
let's look at how we learn
the parameters for all of the users.

121
00:09:19,325 --> 00:09:21,073
To learn the parameters w(1), b(1), w(2),

122
00:09:21,073 --> 00:09:23,631
b(2),...,w(nu), b(nu),

123
00:09:23,631 --> 00:09:30,608
we would take this cost function on
top and sum it over all the nu users.

124
00:09:30,608 --> 00:09:37,647
So we would have sum from
j=1 one to nu of the same

125
00:09:37,647 --> 00:09:44,009
cost function that we
had written up above.

126
00:09:44,009 --> 00:09:47,345
And this becomes the cost for

127
00:09:47,345 --> 00:09:53,186
learning all the parameters for
all of the users.

128
00:09:53,186 --> 00:09:55,456
And if we use gradient descent or

129
00:09:55,456 --> 00:10:00,922
any other optimization algorithm to
minimize this as a function of w(1),

130
00:10:00,922 --> 00:10:05,883
b(1) all the way through w(nu),
b(nu), then you have a pretty

131
00:10:05,883 --> 00:10:10,948
good set of parameters for predicting
movie ratings for all the users.

132
00:10:10,948 --> 00:10:16,736
And you may notice that this algorithm
is a lot like linear regression,

133
00:10:16,736 --> 00:10:22,829
where that plays a role similar to
the output f(x) of linear regression.

134
00:10:22,829 --> 00:10:30,707
Only now we're training a different linear
regression model for each of the nu users.

135
00:10:30,707 --> 00:10:35,757
So that's how you can learn parameters and
predict movie ratings,

136
00:10:35,757 --> 00:10:39,310
if you had access to these features X1 and
X2.

137
00:10:39,310 --> 00:10:43,382
That tell you how much is each of
the movies, a romance movie, and

138
00:10:43,382 --> 00:10:46,284
how much is each of
the movies an action movie?

139
00:10:46,284 --> 00:10:48,247
But where do these features come from?

140
00:10:48,247 --> 00:10:53,206
And what if you don't have access to such
features that give you enough detail

141
00:10:53,206 --> 00:10:56,734
about the movies with wish
to make these predictions?

142
00:10:56,734 --> 00:11:00,630
In the next video, we'll look at
the modification of this algorithm.

143
00:11:00,630 --> 00:11:04,547
They'll let you make predictions
that you make recommendations.

144
00:11:04,547 --> 00:11:09,072
Even if you don't have an advanced
features that describe the items of

145
00:11:09,072 --> 00:11:13,606
the movies in sufficient detail to
run the algorithm that we just saw.

146
00:11:13,606 --> 00:11:16,880
Let's go on and
